<mjml>
  <mj-head>
    <mj-style>
      h2,img,p { margin:0; } td{ padding-top:0 !important; } p {margin-bottom:
      10px;}</mj-style
    >
    <!-- <mj-font name="Roboto" href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css?family=Roboto" /> -->
    <mj-font
      name="Roboto+Serif"
      href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Roboto+Serif:ital,opsz,wght@0,8..144,100..900;1,8..144,100..900&display=swap"
    />
  </mj-head>
  <mj-body background-color="#f0f1f3">
    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>

    <!-- Logo Header -->
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff">
      <mj-spacer height="10px" />
      <mj-column padding="10px 12px 10px 12px" width="100%">
        <mj-spacer height="16px" />
        <mj-image
          padding="10px 12px"
          css-class="light_img"
          width="150px"
          src="https://www.businesshistory.co/logo-gray.png"
          href="https://www.businesshistory.co"
          alt=""
        />

        <mj-divider
          border-width="1px"
          border-style="solid"
          border-color="lightgrey"
          padding="10px 0px"
        />
        <mj-text padding="10px 2px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Every successful company has a turning point—a risk that paid off, a
            product that redefined an industry, or a decision that changed
            everything. However, not every story is one of triumph; some of the
            most valuable lessons come from the failures and missteps that
            shaped the business landscape.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-divider
          border-width="1px"
          border-style="solid"
          border-color="lightgrey"
          padding="0px 0px"
        />
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>

    <mj-spacer height="10px"></mj-spacer>

    <!-- Bussiness history -->
    <!-- <mj-section css-class="mj_fsection" background-color="#ffffff" css-class="mj_fsection">
      <mj-column background-color="#ffffff" width="100%">
        <mj-text padding="2px 12px 0px 12px" font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;" color="white">
          <h2 style="
          padding-top:14px;
          color:#8C3321;
            text-align: left;
            border-bottom:2px solid #8C3321;
              font-size: 26px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              padding-bottom:8px;
            ">
          Reviving oil wells: Hilcorp turns trash into treasure</h2> 
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section> -->

    <!-- Content sections -->
    <mj-section
      css-class="mj_fsection"
      background-color="#ffffff"
      css-class="mj_fsection"
    >
      <mj-column background-color="#ffffff" width="100%">
        <mj-text
          padding="2px 12px 0px 12px"
          font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;"
          color="white"
        >
          <h2
            style="
              padding-top: 14px;
              color: #8c3321;
              text-align: left;
              border-bottom: 2px solid #8c3321;
              font-size: 26px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              padding-bottom: 8px;
            "
          >
            Three establishments that stood the test of time
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <mj-section background-color="#ffffff" padding-bottom="6px">
      <mj-column>
        <mj-spacer height="18px"></mj-spacer>
        <mj-text
          padding="10px 12px"
          font-family="TNYAdobeCaslonPro, 'Times New Roman', serif;"
          color="#000000"
        >
          <h2
            style="
              font-size: 24px;
              line-height: 1.2;
              font-weight: 400;
              margin-top: 2px !important;
            "
          >
            World’s oldest and functioning company
          </h2>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Kongo Gumi’s story begins in 578 AD, when Buddhism was taking root
            in Japan. Prince Shōtoku wanted a proper Buddhist temple built. So,
            he invited Shigemitsu Kongo, a master carpenter from Baekje, in
            modern-day Korea, to construct the Shitennō-ji Temple, Japan’s first
            Buddhist temple. That project launched a legacy that would
            <a
              style="
                text-decoration: none;
                border-bottom: 2px solid #8c3321;
                color: black;
              "
              href="https://link.businesshistory.co/bh-12-07-2025-1-last-over-1400-years?source=website"
              target="_blank"
              >last over 1,400 years</a
            >.
          </p>
        </mj-text>

        <mj-image
          border-radius="10px"
          padding="10px 12px 14px 12px"
          width="600px"
          src="https://www.businesshistory.co/email/images/showa-depression-kongo-gumi-tragedy.jpg"
          alt="The Showa Depression in the 1920s was a challenging period, leading to the tragic suicide of Kongo Haruichi, the 37th leader"
          href="https://www.businesshistory.co"
        />
        <mj-text padding="0px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#A9A7AF">
          <p style="font-size: 12px; line-height: 1.2; color: #a9a7af">
            <i>
              The Showa Depression in the 1920s was a challenging period,
              leading to the tragic suicide of Kongo Haruichi, the 37th leader.
              Credits: Kongo Gumi</i
            >
          </p>
        </mj-text>
        <mj-text padding="10px 12px" font-family="Roboto+Serif" color="#000000">
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5">
            Kongo Gumi's expertise in traditional woodworking and joinery
            techniques made them vital to preserving Japan’s cultural heritage.
            The family-run business was passed down through more than 40
            generations. But things took a turn in the 1980s. Japan’s economic
            bubble encouraged reckless borrowing, and Kongo Gumi, eager to
            diversify, expanded into real estate and development.
          </p>
          <p style="font-size: 16px; line-height: 1.5; filter: blur(5px)">
            When the bubble burst in the 1990s, the company was saddled with
            crushing debt. By 2006, it had accumulated about $343M and was
            forced to file for bankruptcy. That same year, it was absorbed by
            the Takamatsu Construction Group. The family’s direct ownership
            ended, but the company, still called Kongo Gumi, survived,
            continuing to restore temples, pagodas, and other national sites.
            Ironically, what centuries of upheaval couldn’t kill, modern debt
            almost did.
          </p>
        </mj-text>
      </mj-column>
    </mj-section>
    <mj-spacer height="15px"></mj-spacer>
  </mj-body>
</mjml>
